</bibRefCitation>
show that 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFA2F865FFB0CFCD8" authorityName="Belyaev &amp; Litvinova" authorityYear="1972" box="[1051,1188,860,886]" class="Ophiuroidea" genus="Perlophiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55353FF9DFA2F865FFB0CFCD8" box="[1051,1188,860,886]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Perlophiura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the family 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFEA38683FEC8FC34" box="[151,352,896,922]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiosphalmidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophiosphalmidae</taxonomicName>
, sister to the 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55353FF9DFC368683FBF0FC34" box="[514,1112,896,923]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFC368683FC85FC34" baseAuthorityName="Lyman" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[514,813,896,922]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiosphalmidae" genus="Ophiosphalma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="armigerum">Ophiosphalma armigerum</taxonomicName>
- 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFD038683FC14FC34" baseAuthorityName="Lutken &amp; Mortensen" baseAuthorityYear="1899" box="[823,956,896,922]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiosphalmidae" genus="Ophiosphalma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="glabrum">O. glabrum</taxonomicName>
- 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFDF18683FBF0FC34" baseAuthorityName="Koehler" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[965,1112,896,922]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiosphalmidae" genus="Ophiosphalma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="properum">O. properum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
group. However, there was notable genetic divergence between Australian and Clarion-Clipperton Zone samples which indicates there could be more than one species within this genus. The extreme paedomorphic form of these animals (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465353FF9DFAFE86CBFF79FBA9" author="Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. V." pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="0164562" refId="ref35880" refString="Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. V. (2016) Paedomorphosis as an Evolutionary Driving Force: Insights from Deep-Sea Brittle Stars. PLoS ONE, 11, e 0164562. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0164562" type="journal article" year="2016">Stöhr &amp; Martynov 2016</bibRefCitation>
) makes comparison difficult and 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465353FF9DFC7A86EEFCA9FBA9" author="Paterson, G. L. J." box="[590,769,1004,1031]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref35334" refString="Paterson, G. L. J. (1985) The deep-sea Ophiuroidea of the North Atlantic Ocean. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Zoology, 49, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1985">Paterson (1985)</bibRefCitation>
has noted the variation in plating between specimens. The 
<quantity id="887C9B525353FF9DFEA38113FF58FB85" box="[151,240,1040,1067]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
dd MD 
<specimenCount id="5982FD3E5353FF9DFF788113FE73FB84" box="[332,475,1040,1067]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="generic">50 specimen</specimenCount>
has rectangular ventral disc scales on either side of the oral shield which were not figured in the 
<typeStatus id="903F88155353FF9DFF018136FECDFBE1" box="[309,357,1077,1103]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">type</typeStatus>
description. There are 2 arm spines, which are separated near the base of the arm with one short spine being situated ventrally on the distal side of the tentacle pore, but more spine like and lateral in position near the arm tips. It also appears to differ from all published figures of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFDB9817EFBE1FB38" authorityName="Belyaev &amp; Litvinova" authorityYear="1972" box="[909,1097,1148,1174]" class="Ophiuroidea" genus="Perlophiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="profundissima">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55353FF9DFDB9817EFBE1FB38" box="[909,1097,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">P. profundissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a small rectangular first VAP (without adjacent tentacle pores) between the second VAP (with pores) and the jaw slit. This is more in line with the morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFFDC81C7FD25FB70" authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1941" box="[488,653,1220,1246]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiosphalmidae" genus="Ophiosphalma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55353FF9DFFDC81C7FD25FB70" box="[488,653,1220,1246]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ophiosphalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345353FF9DFCFD81C7FCE2FB70" authorityName="Hertz" authorityYear="1927" box="[713,842,1220,1246]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiomusaidae" genus="Ophiomusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55353FF9DFCFD81C7FCE2FB70" box="[713,842,1220,1246]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ophiomusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465353FF9DFDB881C7FB80FB70" author="Hendler, G." box="[908,1064,1220,1246]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="189 - 311" refId="ref31642" refString="Hendler, G. (2018) Armed to the teeth: a new paradigm for the buccal skeleton of brittle stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea). Contributions in Science, 526, 189 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / p. 324539" type="journal article" year="2018">Hendler 2018</bibRefCitation>
fig. 3) where the tentacle pores associated with the first VAP are not visible from the surface, being hidden deep within the jaw slit. More specimens are required to resolve whether there are one or more species in this genus.
</paragraph>
